"Moore K., Doney S.C., Lindsay K., Mahowald N., Michaels Anthony F. A.F.","Nitrogen fixation amplifies the ocean biogeochemical response to decadal timescale variations in mineral dust deposition",2006,"Tellus, Series B: Chemical and Physical Meteorology","58","5",,"560","572",,,10.1111/j.1600-0889.2006.00209.x,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-33750038242&partnerID=40&md5=79ee519d236722411b3f70800189d85c","University of California, Department of Earth System Science, Irvine, CA 92697-3100, United States; Woods Hole Oceanograhic Institution, Department of Marine Chemistry and Geochemistry, Woods Hole, MA 02543-1543, United States; National Center for Atmospheric Research, P.O. Box 3000, Boulder, CO 80307-3000, United States; University of Southern California, Biology Department, Los Angeles, CA 90089-0371, United States","Moore, K., University of California, Department of Earth System Science, Irvine, CA 92697-3100, United States; Doney, S.C., Woods Hole Oceanograhic Institution, Department of Marine Chemistry and Geochemistry, Woods Hole, MA 02543-1543, United States; Lindsay, K., National Center for Atmospheric Research, P.O. Box 3000, Boulder, CO 80307-3000, United States; Mahowald, N., National Center for Atmospheric Research, P.O. Box 3000, Boulder, CO 80307-3000, United States; Michaels Anthony F., A.F., University of Southern California, Biology Department, Los Angeles, CA 90089-0371, United States","A global ocean biogeochemical model is used to quantify the sensitivity of marine biogeochemistry and air-sea CO2 exchange to variations in dust deposition over decadal timescales. Estimates of dust deposition generated under four climate states provide a large range in total deposition with spatially realistic patterns; transient ocean model experiments are conducted by applying a step-function change in deposition from a current climate control. Relative to current conditions, higher dust deposition increases diatom and export production, nitrogen fixation and oceanic net CO2 uptake from the atmosphere, while reduced dust deposition has the opposite effects. Over timescales less than a decade, dust modulation of marine productivity and export is dominated by direct effects in high-nutrient, low-chlorophyll regions, where iron is the primary limiting nutrient. On longer timescales, an indirect nitrogen fixation pathway has increased importance, significantly amplifying the ocean biogeochemical response. Because dust iron input decouples carbon cycling from subsurface macronutrient supply, the ratio of the change in net ocean CO2 uptake to change in export flux is large, 0.45-0.6. Decreasing dust deposition and reduced oceanic CO2 uptake over the next century could provide a positive feedback to global warming, distinct from feedbacks associated with changes in stratification and circulation. © Blackwell Munksgaard, 2006.",,"air-sea interaction; carbon dioxide; decadal variation; deposition; dust; gas exchange; nitrogen cycle; nitrogen fixation; Bacillariophyta",,,,,,"Armstrong, R.A., Lee, C., Hedges, J.I., Honjo, S., Wakeham, S.G., A new, mechanistic model for organic carbon fluxes in the ocean based on the quantitative association of POC with ballast minerals (2002) Deep-Sea Res. Part II, 49, pp. 219-236; Aumont, O., Maier-Reimer, E., Blain, S., Monfray, P., An ecosystem model ofthe global ocean including Fe, Si, P co-limitations (2003) Global Biogeochem. Cycles, 17, p. 1060. , doi 10.1029/2001GB001745; Berman-Frank, I., Cullen, J.T., Shaked, Y., Sherrell, R.M., Falkowski, P.G., Iron availability, cellular iron quotas, and nitrogen fixation in Trichodesmium (2001) Limnol. Oceanogr., 46, pp. 1249-1260; Bopp, L., Kolfield, K.E., Le Quérê, C., Dust impact or morine b:oto and atmospheric CO2 during glacid periods (2003) Paleoceanography, (2), p. 1046. , lp(2), doi: 11029/2002PA000810; Bopp, L., Monfray, P., Aumont, O., Dufresne, J.L., Treut, H.L., Potential impact of climate change on marine export productio